• @stephanielumhnn Aiea Chop Suey is closing for good after Wednesday night. Since the 1960s, the restaurant in the Aiea Shopping Center has been known for its crispy gau gee, honey walnut shrimp and roast duck. The Lin family says they’re tired and it’s time to retire. The owner, Li Min Lin, said rising food prices had nothing to do with the closure, it’s just time to say goodbye.

•MAHALO AUNTY KAREN•
Yesterday morning, we headed to our normal spot for breakfast @karenskitchenhawaii and found out some sad news, that she’s no longer with us anymore and Karen’s was closed indefinitely.
Karen Yamaoka was a staple to the Kaka’ako area for over 30yrs and I’ve been eating there for over 25yrs, from a kid and as an adult working on Queen Street at @caponesultimatedetailautobody and this is a big loss for many.
When she’d be in her kitchen, she’d greet you with a smile and with so much love and aloha, as well as instilled those same values in all of her staff, as they’d do the same and not only could you feel the aloha as you entered, it could be tasted in the food, as she loved cooking for people.
From her early bird breakfast specials that was $5 and under to her famous school style spaghetti to her chop steak and bentos and much more…everything was onolicious!
She was one of the biggest @bettyboop fans, as Karen’s was covered in Betty Boop with memorabilia from all over the world.
Mahalo nui Aunty Karen for your decades of feeding the people of Hawai’i, keeping it local and affordable for all of us, even when everything started to change in Kaka’ako and thank you for treating people like myself as family…you’ll be truly missed and never forgotten. Sending love, aloha, prayers and positive energy during this time to the ‘Ohana. Peace be the journey and see you in the next episode. 🙏🏽❤️💯🕊️ #karenskitchen #karenyamaoka #kakaakoOG #kakaako #oahu #supportlocal #supporthawaii #wegotwe #alohaoe

• @ryspokeshack @ryshawaiilife Hawaii’s sugarcane industry paved our past and present. Much of what we see in today’s culture and food in Hawaii is because of our sugarcane plantations (the Ry’s Ohana came 5 generations ago for farming and better life in Hawaii). 

Reference @lanai on @keepitalohapod for a nice story about Hawaii’s mix plate origin - it was because of immigration, sugarcane industry, and sharing with each other in Hawaii.

@sugahdaddehskanejuice and @haleiwafruitshack could possibly be one of the few or only ohana’s that produce Hawaiian sugarcane from seed to table in modern day Hawaii.

Lotsa pride and passion go into this family business because of its importance to our culture. We hope to see you at the new location in pearlridge (downtown side).

Had to repost this from my Cuzn @ryspokeshack A man came up to the shack today and was looking for one poke bowl, and he didn’t know how to order from our unorthodox kinda menu. He said where he’s from it’s much easier to order because it’s a build-a-bowl system. He insisted we make and choose his bowl.

We made him a poke bowl with two types of poke. Limu poke and Spicy ahi, and we had some crab and cucumber namasu in the center.  My daughter served him the dish and said “thank you for your patience, I hope you enjoy it”. This is her favorite poke bowl.

The man came to me outside and told me he was upset “there is no fruits, no vegetable sides, beef, or chicken on this bowl, this is a terrible poke bowl” I replied we can refund you and tried to explain to him in the nicest way that normally in Hawaii poke bowls is served with poke (fish) over rice (many times there is no sides or extras in da bowl).

I didn’t take this personally (it triggered me enough to post), maybe a few years ago I would have took more time to explain and educate local foods to him and how they probably differ greatly from how he may see or receive mimicked local foods outside of Hawaii.  It all depends how I feel about the customer, and I felt there wasn’t a way to talk to him.  We refunded him and told him we hope you can find a poke bowl you are looking for, because I don’t know any places on island that serve it like he was explaining (maybe Waikiki 🤷‍♂️)

We make poke fresh on order and serve them the exact way we like to eat.  I or my daughter will choose the poke style if you ask us for recommendations (we love doing this), because there is many poke types at our shop.

Overall this was a great learning experience for my daughter to see different interactions, and for her to observe how to properly address situations using some EQ. 

Mahalo nui to all our supporters, please don’t hesitate to let us know anything, just don’t ask why there is no chicken wing in your poke bowl 🤙🏽
